description: The XMLHttpRequest API makes HTTP requests. It's the predecessor to fetch(). Also known as XHR.
description_html: The XMLHttpRequest API makes HTTP requests. It's the predecessor to fetch(). Also known as XHR.
name: XMLHttpRequest

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 7, specifying a Blob as the data to append to the object, the filename reported in the Content-Disposition HTTP header was an empty string, resulting in errors on some servers. Starting with Firefox 7, the filename blob is sent.

firefox_android.notes: Before Firefox for Android 7, specifying a Blob as the data to append to the object, the filename reported in the Content-Disposition HTTP header was an empty string, resulting in errors on some servers. Starting with Firefox for Android 7, the filename blob is sent.

webview_android.notes: XHR in Android 4.0 sends empty content for FormData with blob.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 7, specifying a Blob as the data to append to the object, the filename reported in the Content-Disposition HTTP header was an empty string, resulting in errors on some servers. Starting with Firefox 7, the filename blob is sent.

firefox_android.notes: Before Firefox for Android 7, specifying a Blob as the data to append to the object, the filename reported in the Content-Disposition HTTP header was an empty string, resulting in errors on some servers. Starting with Firefox for Android 7, the filename blob is sent.

ie.notes: With the "Include local directory pass when uploading files to a server" option enabled, IE will change the filename inside the Blob on the fly. To have direct control of the sent filename, the developer should send the filename as the third parameter value, i.e. formData.append(name, value, filename).

webview_android.notes: XHR in Android 4.0 sends empty content for FormData with blob.

firefox.notes: Starting from Firefox 49, empty headers are returned as empty strings in case the preference network.http.keep_empty_response_headers_as_empty_string is set to true, defaulting to false. Before Firefox 49 empty headers had been ignored. Since Firefox 50 the preference defaults to true.

firefox_android.notes: Starting from Firefox for Android 49, empty headers are returned as empty strings in case the preference network.http.keep_empty_response_headers_as_empty_string is set to true, defaulting to false. Before Firefox for Android 49 empty headers had been ignored. Since Firefox for Android 50 the preference defaults to true.

firefox.notes: Starting in Firefox 30, synchronous requests on the main thread have been deprecated due to their negative impact on performance and the user experience. Therefore, the async parameter may not be false except in a Worker.

firefox_android.notes: Starting in Firefox for Android 30, synchronous requests on the main thread have been deprecated due to their negative impact on performance and the user experience. Therefore, the async parameter may not be false except in a Worker.

ie.notes: Before Internet Explorer 10, the value of XMLHttpRequest.responseText could be read only once the request was complete.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 51, an error parsing the received data added a <parsererror> node to the top of the Document and then returned the Document in whatever state it happens to be in. This was inconsistent with the specification. Starting with Firefox 51, this scenario now correctly returns null as per the spec.

firefox_android.notes: Before Firefox for Android 51, an error parsing the received data added a <parsererror> node to the top of the Document and then returned the Document in whatever state it happens to be in. This was inconsistent with the specification. Starting with Firefox for Android 51, this scenario now correctly returns null as per the spec.

safari.notes: Doesn't send the correct Content-Type header by default. See bug 227477.

safari_ios.notes: Doesn't send the correct Content-Type header by default. See bug 227477.

webview_ios.notes: Doesn't send the correct Content-Type header by default. See bug 227477.

ie.notes: Internet Explorer version 5 and 6 supported ajax calls using ActiveXObject()
Internet Explorer version 5 and 6 supported ajax calls using ActiveXObject()

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 11, it's no longer supported to use the withCredentials attribute when performing synchronous requests. Attempting to do so throws an NS_ERROR_DOM_INVALID_ACCESS_ERR exception.

firefox_android.notes: Starting with Firefox for Android 14, it's no longer supported to use the withCredentials attribute when performing synchronous requests. Attempting to do so throws an NS_ERROR_DOM_INVALID_ACCESS_ERR exception.

ie.notes: Internet Explorer versions 8 and 9 supported cross-domain requests (CORS) using XDomainRequest.
